[src:gcp-cloud-storage/cloud-storage] Cloud storage services may be accessed through a colocated cloud computing service, a web service application programming interface (API) or by applications that use the API, such as cloud desktop storage, a cloud storage gateway or Web-based content management systems.
[src:gcp-cloud-storage/cloud-storage] Cloud computing is believed to have been invented by J.
[src:gcp-cloud-storage/cloud-storage] Licklider in the 1960s with his work on ARPANET to connect people and data from anywhere at any time.
[src:gcp-cloud-storage/cloud-storage] In 1983, CompuServe offered its consumer users a small amount of disk space that could be used to store any files they chose to upload.
[src:gcp-cloud-storage/cloud-storage] In 1994, AT&T launched PersonaLink Services, an online platform for personal and business communication and entrepreneurship.
[src:gcp-cloud-storage/cloud-storage] In 2005, Box announced an online file sharing and personal cloud content management service for businesses.
[src:gcp-cloud-storage/cloud-storage] Alibaba Cloud was launched in September 2009, three years after AWS.
[src:gcp-cloud-storage/cloud-storage] As of 2024, Gartner ranked cloud storage platforms as follows: AWS, Google, Microsoft, Oracle, Alibaba, IBM, Huawei and Tencent.
[src:gcp-cloud-storage/cloud-storage] These account for 97% of the global cloud services market.
[src:gcp-cloud-storage/cloud-storage] This rating was based on ability to execute in market and innovation vision.
[src:gcp-cloud-storage/cloud-storage] In 2023, 80% of China's technology companies and half of AI LLM companies ran on Alibaba Cloud while in the US dominance belonged to AWS with 31 to 50% share.
[src:gcp-cloud-storage/cloud-storage] In 2026, Alibaba is scheduled to spend more than 300 million yuan, about $52 billion, on artificial intelligence and cloud infrastructure over the next three years, a figure much larger than the amount spent the previous year.
[src:gcp-cloud-storage/cloud-storage] Data centers will also be expanding, and AI models like Qwen.
[src:gcp-cloud-storage/cloud-storage] Alibaba's CEO, Eddie Wu, describes the amount spent as the largest to date on cloud and AI.
[src:gcp-cloud-storage/cloud-storage] Also, he explained that they expect much of the internal AI workload to run on Alibaba Cloud.
[src:gcp-cloud-storage/cloud-storage] Spending will include specific items such as GPU-like accelerators and large-scale data centers to support internal workloads and external client functions, underscoring Alibaba's pivot from e-commerce to cloud infrastructure.
[src:gcp-cloud-storage/cloud-storage] Cloud storage is based on highly virtualized infrastructure and is like broader cloud computing in terms of interfaces, near-instant elasticity and scalability, multi-tenancy, and metered resources.
[src:gcp-cloud-storage/cloud-storage] Cloud storage services can be used from an off-premises service (Amazon S3) or deployed on-premises (ViON Capacity Services).
[src:gcp-cloud-storage/cloud-storage] There are three types of cloud storage: a hosted object storage service, file storage, and block storage.
[src:gcp-cloud-storage/cloud-storage] Each of these cloud storage types offer their own unique advantages.
[src:gcp-cloud-storage/cloud-storage] Security of stored data and data in transit may be a concern when storing sensitive data at a cloud storage provider.
[src:gcp-cloud-storage/cloud-storage] Outsourcing data storage increases the attack surface area.
[src:gcp-cloud-storage/cloud-storage] Cloud storage is a rich resource for both hackers and national security agencies.
[src:gcp-cloud-storage/cloud-storage] Because the cloud holds data from many different users and organizations, hackers see it as a very valuable target.
[src:gcp-cloud-storage/cloud-storage] The number of people with access to the data who could be compromised (e.g., bribed, or coerced) increases dramatically.
[src:gcp-cloud-storage/cloud-storage] Decryption keys that are kept by the service user, as opposed to the service provider, limit access to data by service provider employees.
[src:gcp-cloud-storage/cloud-storage] As for sharing multiple data in the cloud with multiple users, a large number of keys has to be distributed to users via secure channels for decryption, also it has to be securely stored and managed by the users in their devices.
[src:gcp-cloud-storage/cloud-storage] Storing these keys requires rather expensive secure storage.
[src:gcp-cloud-storage/cloud-storage] To overcome that, key-aggregate cryptosystem can be used.
[src:gcp-cloud-storage/cloud-storage] It increases the number of networks over which the data travels.
[src:gcp-cloud-storage/cloud-storage] Instead of just a local area network (LAN) or storage area network (SAN), data stored on a cloud requires a WAN (wide area network) to connect them both.
[src:gcp-cloud-storage/cloud-storage] By sharing storage and networks with many other users/customers it is possible for other customers to access your data.
[src:gcp-cloud-storage/cloud-storage] Sometimes because of erroneous actions, faulty equipment, a bug and sometimes because of criminal intent.
[src:gcp-cloud-storage/cloud-storage] This risk applies to all types of storage and not only cloud storage.
[src:gcp-cloud-storage/cloud-storage] The risk of having data read during transmission can be mitigated through encryption technology.
[src:gcp-cloud-storage/cloud-storage] Encryption in transit protects data as it is being transmitted to and from the cloud service.
[src:gcp-cloud-storage/cloud-storage] Encryption at rest protects data that is stored at the service provider.
[src:gcp-cloud-storage/cloud-storage] Encrypting data in an on-premises cloud service on-ramp system can provide both kinds of encryption protection.
[src:gcp-cloud-storage/cloud-storage] There are several options available to avoid security issues.
[src:gcp-cloud-storage/cloud-storage] One option is to use a private cloud instead of a public cloud.
[src:gcp-cloud-storage/cloud-storage] Another option is to ingest data in an encrypted format where the key is held within the on-premise infrastructure.
[src:gcp-cloud-storage/cloud-storage] To this end, access is often by use of on-premise cloud storage gateways that have options to encrypt the data prior to transfer.
[src:gcp-cloud-storage/cloud-storage] Typically, cloud storage Service Level Agreements (SLAs) do not encompass all forms of service interruptions.
[src:gcp-cloud-storage/cloud-storage] Exclusions typically include planned maintenance, downtime resulting from external factors such as network issues, human errors like misconfigurations, natural disasters, force majeure events, or security breaches.
[src:gcp-cloud-storage/cloud-storage] Typically, customers bear the responsibility of monitoring SLA compliance and must file claims for any unmet SLAs within a designated timeframe.
[src:gcp-cloud-storage/cloud-storage] Customers should be aware of how deviations from SLAs are calculated, as these parameters may vary by other services offered within the same provider.
[src:gcp-cloud-storage/cloud-storage] These requirements can place a considerable burden on customers.
[src:gcp-cloud-storage/cloud-storage] Additionally, SLA percentages and conditions can differ across various services within the same provider, with some services lacking any SLA altogether.
[src:gcp-cloud-storage/cloud-storage] In cases of service interruptions due to hardware failures in the cloud provider, service providers typically do not offer monetary compensation.
[src:gcp-cloud-storage/cloud-storage] Instead, eligible users may receive credits as outlined in the corresponding SLA.
[src:gcp-cloud-storage/cloud-storage] Hybrid cloud storage is a term for a storage infrastructure that uses a combination of on-premises storage resources with cloud storage.
[src:gcp-cloud-storage/cloud-storage] The on-premises storage is usually managed by the organization, while the public cloud storage provider is responsible for the management and security of the data stored in the cloud.
[src:gcp-cloud-storage/cloud-storage] Hybrid cloud storage can be implemented by an on-premises cloud storage gateway that presents a file system or object storage interface that users can access in the same way they would access a local storage system.
[src:gcp-cloud-storage/cloud-storage] The cloud storage gateway transparently transfers the data to and from the cloud storage service, providing low latency access to the data through a local cache.
[src:gcp-cloud-storage/cloud-storage] Hybrid cloud storage can be used to supplement an organization's internal storage resources, or it can be used as the primary storage infrastructure.
[src:gcp-cloud-storage/cloud-storage] In either case, hybrid cloud storage can provide organizations with greater flexibility and scalability than traditional on-premises storage infrastructure.
[src:gcp-cloud-storage/cloud-storage] There are several benefits to using hybrid cloud storage, including the ability to cache frequently used data on-site for quick access, while inactive cold data is stored off-site in the cloud.
[src:gcp-cloud-storage/cloud-storage] This can save space, reduce storage costs and improve performance.
[src:gcp-cloud-storage/cloud-storage] Additionally, hybrid cloud storage can provide organizations with greater redundancy and fault tolerance, as data is stored in both on-premises and cloud storage infrastructure.
[src:gcp-cloud-storage/data-lake] A **data lake** is a system or repository of data stored in its natural, raw format, usually object blobs or files.
[src:gcp-cloud-storage/data-lake] A data lake is usually a single store of data including raw copies of source system data, sensor data, social data etc., and transformed data used for tasks such as reporting, visualization, advanced analytics, and machine learning.
[src:gcp-cloud-storage/data-lake] A data lake can include structured data from relational databases (rows and columns), semi-structured data (CSV, logs, XML, JSON), unstructured data (emails, documents, PDFs), and binary data (images, audio, video).
[src:gcp-cloud-storage/data-lake] A data lake can be established *on premises* (within an organization's data centers) or *in the cloud* (using cloud services).
[src:gcp-cloud-storage/data-lake] James Dixon, then chief technology officer at Pentaho, coined the term by 2011 to contrast it with data mart, which is a smaller repository of interesting attributes derived from raw data.
[src:gcp-cloud-storage/data-lake] In promoting data lakes, he argued that data marts have several inherent problems, such as information siloing.
[src:gcp-cloud-storage/data-lake] PricewaterhouseCoopers (PwC) said that data lakes could "put an end to data silos".
[src:gcp-cloud-storage/data-lake] Many companies use cloud storage services such as Google Cloud Storage and Amazon S3 or a distributed file system such as Apache Hadoop distributed file system (HDFS).
[src:gcp-cloud-storage/data-lake] There is a gradual academic interest in the concept of data lakes.
[src:gcp-cloud-storage/data-lake] For example, Personal DataLake at Cardiff University is a new type of data lake which aims at managing big data of individual users by providing a single point of collecting, organizing, and sharing personal data.
[src:gcp-cloud-storage/data-lake] Early data lakes, such as Hadoop 1.0, had limited capabilities because it only supported batch-oriented processing (Map Reduce).
[src:gcp-cloud-storage/data-lake] Interacting with it required expertise in Java, map reduce and higher-level tools like Apache Pig, Apache Spark and Apache Hive (which were also originally batch-oriented).
[src:gcp-cloud-storage/data-lake] Poorly managed data lakes have been facetiously called data swamps.
[src:gcp-cloud-storage/data-lake] In June 2015, David Needle characterized "so-called data lakes" as "one of the more controversial ways to manage big data".
[src:gcp-cloud-storage/data-lake] PwC was also careful to note in their research that not all data lake initiatives are successful.
[src:gcp-cloud-storage/data-lake] They describe companies that build successful data lakes as gradually maturing their lake as they figure out which data and metadata are important to the organization.
[src:gcp-cloud-storage/data-lake] Another criticism is that the term *data lake* is used with many different meanings.
[src:gcp-cloud-storage/data-lake] It may be used to refer to, for example: any tools or data management practices that are not data warehouses; a particular technology for implementation; a raw data reservoir; a hub for ETL offload; or a central hub for self-service analytics.
[src:gcp-cloud-storage/data-lake] While critiques of data lakes are warranted, in many cases they apply to other data projects as well.
[src:gcp-cloud-storage/data-lake] For example, the definition of *data warehouse* is also changeable, and not all data warehouse efforts have been successful.
[src:gcp-cloud-storage/data-lake] In response to various critiques, McKinsey noted that the data lake should be viewed as a service model for delivering business value within the enterprise, not a technology outcome.
[src:gcp-cloud-storage/erasure-code] The fraction *r* = *k*/*n* is called the code rate.
[src:gcp-cloud-storage/erasure-code] The fraction *k’/k*, where *k’* denotes the number of symbols required for recovery, is called reception efficiency.
[src:gcp-cloud-storage/erasure-code] The recovery algorithm expects that it is known which of the *n* symbols are lost.
[src:gcp-cloud-storage/erasure-code] Erasure coding was invented by Irving Reed and Gustave Solomon in 1960.
[src:gcp-cloud-storage/erasure-code] There are many different erasure coding schemes.
[src:gcp-cloud-storage/erasure-code] The most popular erasure codes are Reed-Solomon coding, low-density parity-check code (LDPC codes), and turbo codes.
[src:gcp-cloud-storage/erasure-code] While technically RAID can be seen as a kind of erasure code, RAID is generally applied to an array attached to a single host computer (which is a single point of failure), while "erasure coding" generally implies multiple hosts, sometimes called a redundant array of inexpensive servers (RAIS).
[src:gcp-cloud-storage/erasure-code] The erasure code allows operations to continue when any one of those hosts stops.
[src:gcp-cloud-storage/erasure-code] Compared to block-level RAID systems, object storage erasure coding has some significant differences that make it more resilient.
[src:gcp-cloud-storage/erasure-code] Optimal erasure codes have the property that any *k* out of the *n* code word symbols are sufficient to recover the original message (i.e., they have optimal reception efficiency).
[src:gcp-cloud-storage/erasure-code] Optimal erasure codes are maximum distance separable codes (MDS codes).
[src:gcp-cloud-storage/erasure-code] Parity check is the special case where *n*= *k* + 1.
[src:gcp-cloud-storage/erasure-code] The set of *k* + 1 values $\{v_{i}\}_{1\leq i\leq k+1}$ is now consistent with regard to the checksum.
[src:gcp-cloud-storage/erasure-code] RAID 5 is a widely used application of the parity check erasure code using XOR.
[src:gcp-cloud-storage/erasure-code] In the simple case where *k* = 2, redundancy symbols may be created by sampling different points along the line between the two original symbols.
[src:gcp-cloud-storage/erasure-code] Alice wants to send her telephone number (555629) to Bob using err-mail.
[src:gcp-cloud-storage/erasure-code] Messages longer than 5 characters are illegal.
[src:gcp-cloud-storage/erasure-code] It is very expensive (similar to air-mail).
[src:gcp-cloud-storage/erasure-code] Instead of asking Bob to acknowledge the messages she sends, Alice devises the following scheme.
[src:gcp-cloud-storage/erasure-code] Bob knows that the form of *f*(*k*) is $f(i)=a+(b-a)(i-1)$ , where *a* and *b* are the two parts of the telephone number.
[src:gcp-cloud-storage/erasure-code] Bob can reconstruct Alice's phone number by computing the values of *a* and *b* from the values (*f*(4) and *f*(5)) he has received.
[src:gcp-cloud-storage/erasure-code] Bob can perform this procedure using any two err-mails, so the erasure code in this example has a rate of 40%.
[src:gcp-cloud-storage/erasure-code] Note that Alice cannot encode her telephone number in just one err-mail, because it contains six characters, and that the maximum length of one err-mail message is five characters.
[src:gcp-cloud-storage/erasure-code] If she sent her phone number in pieces, asking Bob to acknowledge receipt of each piece, at least four messages would have to be sent anyway (two from Alice, and two acknowledgments from Bob).
[src:gcp-cloud-storage/erasure-code] So the erasure code in this example, which requires five messages, is quite economical.
[src:gcp-cloud-storage/erasure-code] For truly generic erasure codes that work over any data set, we would need something other than the *f*(*i*) given.
[src:gcp-cloud-storage/erasure-code] The linear construction above can be generalized to polynomial interpolation.
[src:gcp-cloud-storage/erasure-code] Additionally, points are now computed over a finite field.
[src:gcp-cloud-storage/erasure-code] First we choose a finite field *F* with order of at least *n*, but usually a power of 2.
[src:gcp-cloud-storage/erasure-code] The sender numbers the data symbols from 0 to *k* − 1 and sends them.
[src:gcp-cloud-storage/erasure-code] He then constructs a (Lagrange) polynomial *p*(*x*) of order *k* such that *p*(*i*) is equal to data symbol *i*.
[src:gcp-cloud-storage/erasure-code] The receiver can now also use polynomial interpolation to recover the lost packets, provided he receives *k* symbols successfully.
[src:gcp-cloud-storage/erasure-code] If the order of *F* is less than 2*b*, where b is the number of bits in a symbol, then multiple polynomials can be used.
[src:gcp-cloud-storage/erasure-code] The sender can construct symbols *k* to *n* − 1 'on the fly', i.e., distribute the workload evenly between transmission of the symbols.
[src:gcp-cloud-storage/erasure-code] If the receiver wants to do his calculations 'on the fly', he can construct a new polynomial *q*, such that *q*(*i*) = *p*(*i*) if symbol *i* < *k* was received successfully and *q*(*i*) = 0 when symbol *i* < *k* was not received.
[src:gcp-cloud-storage/erasure-code] Firstly we know that *r*(*i*) = 0 if symbol *i* < *k* has been received successfully.
[src:gcp-cloud-storage/erasure-code] Secondly, if symbol *i* ≥ *k* has been received successfully, then *r*(*i*) = *p*(*i*) − *q*(*i*) can be calculated.
[src:gcp-cloud-storage/erasure-code] So we have enough data points to construct *r* and evaluate it to find the lost packets.
[src:gcp-cloud-storage/erasure-code] So both the sender and the receiver require *O*(*n* (*n* − *k*)) operations and only *O*(*n* − *k*) space for operating 'on the fly'.
[src:gcp-cloud-storage/erasure-code] This process is implemented by Reed–Solomon codes, with code words constructed over a finite field using a Vandermonde matrix.
[src:gcp-cloud-storage/erasure-code] Most practical erasure codes are systematic codes—each one of the original *k* symbols can be found copied, unencoded, as one of the *n* message symbols.
[src:gcp-cloud-storage/erasure-code] (Erasure codes that support secret sharing never use a systematic code).
[src:gcp-cloud-storage/erasure-code] Fountain codes (also known as *rateless erasure codes*) are notable examples of *near-optimal erasure codes*.
[src:gcp-cloud-storage/erasure-code] They can transform a *k* symbol message into a practically infinite encoded form, i.e., they can generate an arbitrary amount of redundancy symbols that can all be used for error correction.
[src:gcp-cloud-storage/erasure-code] Receivers can start decoding after they have received slightly more than *k* encoded symbols.
[src:gcp-cloud-storage/erasure-code] Regenerating codes address the issue of rebuilding (also called repairing) lost encoded fragments from existing encoded fragments.
[src:gcp-cloud-storage/erasure-code] This issue occurs in distributed storage systems where communication to maintain encoded redundancy is a problem.
[src:gcp-cloud-storage/erasure-code] Erasure coding is now standard practice for reliable data storage.
[src:gcp-cloud-storage/erasure-code] In particular, various implementations of Reed-Solomon erasure coding are used by Apache Hadoop, the RAID-6 built into Linux, Microsoft Azure, Facebook cold storage, and Backblaze Vaults.
[src:gcp-cloud-storage/erasure-code] The classical way to recover from failures in storage systems was to use replication.
[src:gcp-cloud-storage/erasure-code] However, replication incurs significant overhead in terms of wasted bytes.
[src:gcp-cloud-storage/erasure-code] Therefore, increasingly large storage systems, such as those used in data centers use erasure-coded storage.
[src:gcp-cloud-storage/erasure-code] The most common form of erasure coding used in storage systems is Reed-Solomon (RS) code, an advanced mathematics formula used to enable regeneration of missing data from pieces of known data, called parity blocks.
[src:gcp-cloud-storage/erasure-code] In a (*k*, *r*) RS code, a given set of *k* data blocks, called "chunks", are encoded into (*k* + *r*) chunks.
[src:gcp-cloud-storage/erasure-code] The total set of chunks comprises a *stripe*.
[src:gcp-cloud-storage/erasure-code] The coding is done such that as long as at least *k* out of (*k* + *r*) chunks are available, one can recover the entire data.
[src:gcp-cloud-storage/erasure-code] This means a (*k*, *r*) RS-encoded storage can tolerate up to *r* failures.
[src:gcp-cloud-storage/erasure-code] In the case of a fully replicated system, the 10 MB of user data will have to be replicated 4 times to tolerate up to 4 concurrent failures.
[src:gcp-cloud-storage/erasure-code] The storage overhead in that case will be 50/10 = 5.0×.
[src:gcp-cloud-storage/erasure-code] This gives an idea of the lower storage overhead of erasure-coded storage compared to full replication and thus the attraction in today's storage systems.
[src:gcp-cloud-storage/erasure-code] The *Hitchhiker* scheme can be combined with RS-coding to reduce the amount of computation and data-transfer required for data block reconstruction.
[src:gcp-cloud-storage/erasure-code] It is also implemented as an HDFS codec, though a policy will need to be manually defined for it to be used.
[src:gcp-cloud-storage/erasure-code] Initially, erasure codes were used to reduce the cost of storing "cold" (rarely-accessed) data efficiently; but erasure codes can also be used to improve performance serving "hot" (more-frequently-accessed) data compared to simpler redundancy schemes (mirroring).
[src:gcp-cloud-storage/erasure-code] The classic example of erasing coding improving performance is RAID 5, which provides the same single-drive failure protection while requiring fewer hard drives compared to RAID 1.
[src:gcp-cloud-storage/erasure-code] The extra hard drives may then be used to store more data and make use of the improved read/write-speed multiplier on RAID 5.
[src:gcp-cloud-storage/erasure-code] This also applies to RAID 6 (double-redundancy: one parity and one erasure code), assuming processing power is sufficient.
[src:gcp-cloud-storage/erasure-code] Generalized RAID can work with any number of redundancy drives.
[src:gcp-cloud-storage/erasure-code] There are two notations for generalized RAID: RAID7.*x* refers to a system with *x* redundancy drives, allowing recovery when as many as *x* drives fail.
[src:gcp-cloud-storage/erasure-code] Alternatively, RAID N+M refers to N regular data drives with M redundancy drives, being able to recover all the data when any M drives fail.
[src:gcp-cloud-storage/erasure-code] A more advanced example is *EC-Cache*, a cluster cache, i.e. a cache distributed among several nodes.
[src:gcp-cloud-storage/erasure-code] Such systems can suffer from load imbalance when one node happens to host more popular items and a common method to address this issue is *selective replication*, i.e. create more replicas for more popular objects.
[src:gcp-cloud-storage/erasure-code] However, this method is limited by the available amount of memory.
[src:gcp-cloud-storage/erasure-code] By individually dividing *every* object into *k* splits and *r* redundancy units, perfect load balancing can instead be achieved with minimal waste of memory.
[src:gcp-cloud-storage/google-cloud-platform] Google Cloud provides infrastructure as a service, platform as a service, and serverless computing environments.
[src:gcp-cloud-storage/google-cloud-platform] In April 2008, Google announced App Engine, a platform for developing and hosting web applications in Google-managed data centers, which was the first cloud computing service from the company.
[src:gcp-cloud-storage/google-cloud-platform] The service became generally available in November 2011.
[src:gcp-cloud-storage/google-cloud-platform] Since the announcement of App Engine, Google added multiple cloud services to the platform.
[src:gcp-cloud-storage/google-cloud-platform] Google lists over 100 products under the Google Cloud brand.
[src:gcp-cloud-storage/google-cloud-platform] Some of the key services are listed below.
[src:gcp-cloud-storage/google-cloud-platform] A region is a specific geographical location where users can deploy cloud resources.
[src:gcp-cloud-storage/google-cloud-platform] Each region is an independent geographic area that consists of zones.
[src:gcp-cloud-storage/google-cloud-platform] A zone is a deployment area for Google Cloud Platform resources within a region.
[src:gcp-cloud-storage/google-cloud-platform] Zones should be considered a single failure domain within a region.
[src:gcp-cloud-storage/google-cloud-platform] As of Q1 2024, Google Cloud Platform is available in 40 regions and 121 zones.
[src:gcp-cloud-storage/google-cloud-platform] For those familiar with other notable cloud service providers, a comparison of similar services may be helpful in understanding Google Cloud Platform's offerings.
[src:gcp-cloud-storage/google-cloud-platform] Customers announced in 2023 include Kingfisher plc, the Government of Kuwait, Deutsche Börse Group, Unity Technologies, Uber, FanCode, Daimler, and Wix.com.
[src:gcp-cloud-storage/google-cloud-storage] User activation is resourced through the API Developer Console.
[src:gcp-cloud-storage/google-cloud-storage] Google Account holders must first access the service by logging in and then agreeing to the Terms of Service, followed by enabling a billing structure.
[src:gcp-cloud-storage/google-cloud-storage] Google Cloud Storage stores objects (originally limited to 100 GiB, currently up to 5 TiB) in projects which are organized into buckets.
[src:gcp-cloud-storage/google-cloud-storage] All requests are authorized using Identity and Access Management policies or access control lists associated with a user or service account.
[src:gcp-cloud-storage/google-cloud-storage] Google Cloud Storage offers four storage classes, identical in throughput, latency and durability.
[src:gcp-cloud-storage/google-cloud-storage] The four classes, Multi-Regional Storage, Regional Storage, Nearline Storage, and Coldline Storage, differ in their pricing, minimum storage durations, and availability.
[src:gcp-cloud-storage/google-cloud-storage] Google Cloud Storage provides a durability guarantee of 99.999999999% (referred to as "11 nines"), primarily addressing data loss from hardware failures.
[src:gcp-cloud-storage/google-cloud-storage] However, this guarantee does not extend to losses resulting from human errors (such as accidental deletion), misconfigurations, third-party failures and subsequent data corruptions, natural disasters, force majeure events, or security breaches.
[src:gcp-cloud-storage/google-cloud-storage] Customers are responsible for monitoring SLA compliance and must submit claims for any unmet SLAs within a designated timeframe.
[src:gcp-cloud-storage/google-cloud-storage] They should understand how deviations from SLAs are calculated, as these parameters may differ from those of other Google Cloud services.
[src:gcp-cloud-storage/google-cloud-storage] These requirements can impose a significant burden on customers.
[src:gcp-cloud-storage/google-cloud-storage] Additionally, SLA percentages and conditions can vary from those of other Google Cloud services.
[src:gcp-cloud-storage/google-cloud-storage] In cases of data loss due to hardware failure attributable to Google Cloud Platform, the company does not provide monetary compensation; instead, affected users may receive credits if they meet the eligibility criteria.
[src:gcp-cloud-storage/object-storage] Object storage systems allow retention of massive amounts of unstructured data in which data is written once and read once (or many times).
[src:gcp-cloud-storage/object-storage] Object storage is used for purposes such as storing objects like videos and photos on Facebook, songs on Spotify, or files in online collaboration services, such as Dropbox.
[src:gcp-cloud-storage/object-storage] One of the limitations with object storage is that it is not intended for transactional data, as object storage was not designed to replace NAS file access and sharing; it does not support the locking and sharing mechanisms needed to maintain a single, accurately updated version of a file.
[src:gcp-cloud-storage/object-storage] Jim Starkey coined the term ***blob*** working at Digital Equipment Corporation to refer to opaque data entities.
[src:gcp-cloud-storage/object-storage] The terminology was adopted for Rdb/VMS.
[src:gcp-cloud-storage/object-storage] *Blob* is often humorously explained to be an abbreviation for *binary large object*.
[src:gcp-cloud-storage/object-storage] According to Starkey, this backronym arose when Terry McKiever, working in marketing at Apollo Computer felt that the term needed to be an abbreviation.
[src:gcp-cloud-storage/object-storage] McKiever began using the expansion *basic large object*.
[src:gcp-cloud-storage/object-storage] This was later eclipsed by the retroactive explanation of blobs as *binary large objects*.
[src:gcp-cloud-storage/object-storage] According to Starkey, "Blob don't stand for nothin'." Rejecting the acronym, he explained his motivation behind the coinage, saying, "A blob is the thing that ate Cincinnatti [*sic*], Cleveland, or whatever", referring to the 1958 science fiction film *The Blob*.
[src:gcp-cloud-storage/object-storage] In 1995, research led by Garth Gibson on Network-Attached Secure Disks first promoted the concept of splitting less common operations, like namespace manipulations, from common operations, like reads and writes, to optimize the performance and scale of both.
[src:gcp-cloud-storage/object-storage] In the same year, a Belgian company – FilePool – was established to build the basis for archiving functions.
[src:gcp-cloud-storage/object-storage] Object storage was proposed at Gibson's Carnegie Mellon University lab as a research project in 1996.
[src:gcp-cloud-storage/object-storage] Another key concept was abstracting the writes and reads of data to more flexible data containers (objects).
[src:gcp-cloud-storage/object-storage] Fine grained access control through object storage architecture was further described by one of the NASD team, Howard Gobioff, who later was one of the inventors of the Google File System.
[src:gcp-cloud-storage/object-storage] Other related work includes the Coda filesystem project at Carnegie Mellon, which started in 1987, and spawned the Lustre file system.
[src:gcp-cloud-storage/object-storage] There is also the OceanStore project at UC Berkeley, which started in 1999 and the Logistical Networking project at the University of Tennessee Knoxville, which started in 1998.
[src:gcp-cloud-storage/object-storage] In 1999, Gibson founded Panasas to commercialize the concepts developed by the NASD team.
[src:gcp-cloud-storage/object-storage] Seagate Technology played a central role in the development of object storage.
[src:gcp-cloud-storage/object-storage] This paper was proposed to INCITS T-10 (International Committee for Information Technology Standards) with a goal to form a committee and design a specification based on the SCSI interface protocol.
[src:gcp-cloud-storage/object-storage] This defined objects as abstracted data, with unique identifiers and metadata, how objects related to file systems, along with many other innovative concepts.
[src:gcp-cloud-storage/object-storage] Anderson presented many of these ideas at the SNIA conference in October 1999.
[src:gcp-cloud-storage/object-storage] The presentation revealed an IP Agreement that had been signed in February 1997 between the original collaborators (with Seagate represented by Anderson and Chris Malakapalli) and covered the benefits of object storage, scalable computing, platform independence, and storage management.
[src:gcp-cloud-storage/object-storage] One of the design principles of object storage is to abstract some of the lower layers of storage away from the administrators and applications.
[src:gcp-cloud-storage/object-storage] Thus, data is exposed and managed as objects instead of blocks or (exclusively) files.
[src:gcp-cloud-storage/object-storage] Objects contain additional descriptive properties which can be used for better indexing or management.
[src:gcp-cloud-storage/object-storage] Administrators do not have to perform lower-level storage functions like constructing and managing logical volumes to utilize disk capacity or setting RAID levels to deal with disk failure.
[src:gcp-cloud-storage/object-storage] Object storage also allows the addressing and identification of individual objects by more than just file name and file path.
[src:gcp-cloud-storage/object-storage] Object storage adds a unique identifier within a bucket, or across the entire system, to support much larger namespaces and eliminate name collisions.
[src:gcp-cloud-storage/object-storage] Object storage explicitly separates file metadata from data to support additional capabilities.
[src:gcp-cloud-storage/object-storage] Object storage provides programmatic interfaces to allow applications to manipulate data.
[src:gcp-cloud-storage/object-storage] At the base level, this includes Create, read, update and delete (CRUD) functions for basic read, write and delete operations.
[src:gcp-cloud-storage/object-storage] Some object storage implementations go further, supporting additional functionality like object/file versioning, object replication, life-cycle management and movement of objects between different tiers and types of storage.
[src:gcp-cloud-storage/object-storage] Most API implementations are REST-based, allowing the use of many standard HTTP calls.
[src:gcp-cloud-storage/object-storage] The vast majority of cloud storage available in the market leverages an object-storage architecture.
[src:gcp-cloud-storage/object-storage] Some notable examples are Amazon S3, which debuted in March 2006, Microsoft Azure Blob Storage, IBM Cloud Object Storage, Rackspace Cloud Files (whose code was donated in 2010 to Openstack project and released as OpenStack Swift), and Google Cloud Storage released in May 2010.
[src:gcp-cloud-storage/object-storage] Some distributed file systems use an object-based architecture, where file metadata is stored in metadata servers and file data is stored in object storage servers.
[src:gcp-cloud-storage/object-storage] File system client software interacts with the distinct servers, and abstracts them to present a full file system to users and applications.
[src:gcp-cloud-storage/object-storage] Some early incarnations of object storage were used for archiving, as implementations were optimized for data services like immutability, not performance.
[src:gcp-cloud-storage/object-storage] EMC Centera and Hitachi HCP (formerly known as HCAP) are two commonly cited object storage products for archiving.
[src:gcp-cloud-storage/object-storage] Another example is Quantum ActiveScale Object Storage Platform.
[src:gcp-cloud-storage/object-storage] More general-purpose object-storage systems came to market around 2008.
[src:gcp-cloud-storage/object-storage] A few object-storage systems support Unified File and Object storage, allowing clients to store objects on a storage system while simultaneously other clients store files on the same storage system.
[src:gcp-cloud-storage/object-storage] Other vendors in the area of Hybrid cloud storage are using Cloud storage gateways to provide a file access layer over object storage, implementing file access protocols such as SMB and NFS.
[src:gcp-cloud-storage/object-storage] Some large Internet companies developed their own software when object-storage products were not commercially available or use cases were very specific.
[src:gcp-cloud-storage/object-storage] Facebook famously invented their own object-storage software, code-named Haystack, to address their particular massive-scale photo management needs efficiently.
[src:gcp-cloud-storage/object-storage] Object storage at the protocol and device layer was proposed 20 years ago and approved for the SCSI command set nearly 10 years ago as "Object-based Storage Device Commands" (OSD), however, it had not been put into production until the development of the Seagate Kinetic Open Storage platform.
[src:gcp-cloud-storage/object-storage] The SCSI command set for Object Storage Devices was developed by a working group of the SNIA for the T10 committee of the International Committee for Information Technology Standards (INCITS).
[src:gcp-cloud-storage/object-storage] T10 is responsible for all SCSI standards.
[src:gcp-cloud-storage/object-storage] One of the first object-storage products, Lustre, is used in 70% of the Top 100 supercomputers and ~50% of the Top 500.
[src:gcp-cloud-storage/object-storage] As of June 16, 2013, this includes 7 of the top 10, including the current fourth fastest system on the list - China's Tianhe-2 and the seventh fastest, the Titan supercomputer at the Oak Ridge National Laboratory.
[src:gcp-cloud-storage/object-storage] Object-storage systems had good adoption in the early 2000s as an archive platform, particularly in the wake of compliance laws like Sarbanes-Oxley.
[src:gcp-cloud-storage/object-storage] After five years in the market, EMC's Centera product claimed over 3,500 customers and 150 petabytes shipped by 2007.
[src:gcp-cloud-storage/object-storage] Hitachi's HCP product also claims many petabyte-scale customers.
[src:gcp-cloud-storage/object-storage] Newer object storage systems have also gotten some traction, particularly around very large custom applications like eBay's auction site, where EMC Atmos is used to manage over 500 million objects a day.
[src:gcp-cloud-storage/object-storage] As of March 3, 2014, EMC claims to have sold over 1.5 exabytes of Atmos storage.
[src:gcp-cloud-storage/object-storage] On July 1, 2014, Los Alamos National Lab chose the Scality RING as the basis for a 500-petabyte storage environment, which would be among the largest ever.
[src:gcp-cloud-storage/object-storage] "Captive" object storage systems like Facebook's Haystack have scaled impressively.
[src:gcp-cloud-storage/object-storage] In April 2009, Haystack was managing 60 billion photos and 1.5 petabytes of storage, adding 220 million photos and 25 terabytes a week.
[src:gcp-cloud-storage/object-storage] Facebook more recently stated that they were adding 350 million photos a day and were storing 240 billion photos.
[src:gcp-cloud-storage/object-storage] This could equal as much as 357 petabytes.
[src:gcp-cloud-storage/object-storage] Cloud storage has become pervasive as many new web and mobile applications choose it as a common way to store binary data.
[src:gcp-cloud-storage/object-storage] As the storage back-end to many popular applications like Smugmug and Dropbox, Amazon S3 has grown to massive scale, citing over 2-trillion objects stored in April 2013.
[src:gcp-cloud-storage/object-storage] Two months later, Microsoft claimed that they stored even more objects in Azure at 8.5 trillion.
[src:gcp-cloud-storage/object-storage] By April 2014, Azure claimed over 20-trillion objects stored.
[src:gcp-cloud-storage/object-storage] Windows Azure Storage manages Blobs (user files), Tables (structured storage), and Queues (message delivery) and counts them all as objects.
[src:gcp-cloud-storage/object-storage] Coldago Research adopted qualitative and quantitative analysis of the object storage market to rank 13 notable vendors based on technological capabilities, market momentum, and innovation trajectory.
[src:gcp-cloud-storage/object-storage] The 2024 Coldago object storage market leader rating is in alphabetical order: Cloudian, DataCore, Dell EMC, Huawei, IBM, MinIO, Pure Storage, Quantum, and VAST Data.
[src:gcp-cloud-storage/object-storage] In the first version of the OSD standard, objects are specified with a 64-bit partition ID and a 64-bit object ID.
[src:gcp-cloud-storage/object-storage] Partitions are created and deleted within an OSD, and objects are created and deleted within partitions.
[src:gcp-cloud-storage/object-storage] There are no fixed sizes associated with partitions or objects; they are allowed to grow subject to physical size limitations of the device or logical quota constraints on a partition.
[src:gcp-cloud-storage/object-storage] An extensible set of attributes describe objects.
[src:gcp-cloud-storage/object-storage] Some attributes are implemented directly by the OSD, such as the number of bytes in an object and the modification time of an object.
[src:gcp-cloud-storage/object-storage] There is a special policy tag attribute that is part of the security mechanism.
[src:gcp-cloud-storage/object-storage] Other attributes are uninterpreted by the OSD.
[src:gcp-cloud-storage/object-storage] These are set on objects by the higher-level storage systems that use the OSD for persistent storage.
[src:gcp-cloud-storage/object-storage] For example, attributes might be used to classify objects, or to capture relationships among different objects stored on different OSDs.
[src:gcp-cloud-storage/object-storage] A list command returns a list of identifiers for objects within a partition, optionally filtered by matches against their attribute values.
[src:gcp-cloud-storage/object-storage] A list command can also return selected attributes of the listed objects.
[src:gcp-cloud-storage/object-storage] Read and write commands can be combined, or piggy-backed, with commands to get and set attributes.
[src:gcp-cloud-storage/object-storage] This ability reduces the number of times a high-level storage system has to cross the interface to the OSD, which can improve overall efficiency.
[src:gcp-cloud-storage/object-storage] A second generation of the SCSI command set, "Object-Based Storage Devices - 2" (OSD-2) added support for snapshots, collections of objects, and improved error handling.
[src:gcp-cloud-storage/object-storage] A snapshot is a point-in-time copy of all the objects in a partition into a new partition.
[src:gcp-cloud-storage/object-storage] The OSD can implement a space-efficient copy using copy-on-write techniques so that the two partitions share objects that are unchanged between the snapshots, or the OSD might physically copy the data to the new partition.
[src:gcp-cloud-storage/object-storage] The standard defines clones, which are writeable, and snapshots, which are read-only.
[src:gcp-cloud-storage/object-storage] A collection is a special kind of object that contains the identifiers of other objects.
[src:gcp-cloud-storage/object-storage] There are operations to add and delete from collections, and there are operations to get or set attributes for all the objects in a collection.
[src:gcp-cloud-storage/object-storage] Collections are also used for error reporting.
[src:gcp-cloud-storage/object-storage] If an object becomes damaged by the occurrence of a media defect (i.e., a bad spot on the disk) or by a software error within the OSD implementation, its identifier is put into a special error collection.
[src:gcp-cloud-storage/object-storage] The higher-level storage system that uses the OSD can query this collection and take corrective action as necessary.
[src:gcp-cloud-storage/object-storage] The border between an object store and a key–value store is blurred, with key–value stores being sometimes loosely referred to as object stores.
[src:gcp-cloud-storage/object-storage] A traditional block storage interface uses a series of fixed size blocks which are numbered starting at 0.
[src:gcp-cloud-storage/object-storage] Data must be that exact fixed size and can be stored in a particular block which is identified by its logical block number (LBN).
[src:gcp-cloud-storage/object-storage] Later, one can retrieve that block of data by specifying its unique LBN.
[src:gcp-cloud-storage/object-storage] With a key–value store, data is identified by a key rather than a LBN.
[src:gcp-cloud-storage/object-storage] A key might be "cat" or "olive" or "42".
[src:gcp-cloud-storage/object-storage] It can be an arbitrary sequence of bytes of arbitrary length.
[src:gcp-cloud-storage/object-storage] Data (called a value in this parlance) does not need to be a fixed size and also can be an arbitrary sequence of bytes of arbitrary length.
[src:gcp-cloud-storage/object-storage] One stores data by presenting the key and data (value) to the data store and can later retrieve the data by presenting the key.
[src:gcp-cloud-storage/object-storage] This concept is seen in programming languages.
[src:gcp-cloud-storage/object-storage] Python calls them dictionaries, Perl calls them hashes, Java, Rust and C++ call them maps, etc.
[src:gcp-cloud-storage/object-storage] Several data stores also implement key–value stores such as Memcached, Redis and CouchDB.
[src:gcp-cloud-storage/object-storage] Object stores are similar to key–value stores in two respects.
[src:gcp-cloud-storage/object-storage] First, the object identifier or URL (the equivalent of the key) can be an arbitrary string.
[src:gcp-cloud-storage/object-storage] Second, data may be of an arbitrary size.
[src:gcp-cloud-storage/object-storage] There are, however, a few key differences between key–value stores and object stores.
[src:gcp-cloud-storage/object-storage] First, object stores also allow one to associate a limited set of attributes (metadata) with each piece of data.
[src:gcp-cloud-storage/object-storage] The combination of a key, value, and set of attributes is referred to as an object.
[src:gcp-cloud-storage/object-storage] Second, object stores are optimized for large amounts of data (hundreds of megabytes or even gigabytes), whereas for key–value stores the value is expected to be relatively small (kilobytes).
[src:gcp-cloud-storage/object-storage] Finally, object stores usually offer weaker consistency guarantees such as eventual consistency, whereas key–value stores offer strong consistency.
